  "description": "The dimension of a vector space is the number of vectors in any basis — the number of independent directions in the space. The real line R\\mathbb{R} is one-dimensional: a single number determines a point. The plane R2\\mathbb{R}^2 is two-dimensional: you need two numbers (an xx-coordinate and a yy-coordinate). Ordinary space R3\\mathbb{R}^3 is three-dimensional: three numbers are needed. The pattern extends: Rn\\mathbb{R}^n has dimension nn, meaning nn independent numbers are needed to specify a point.\nDimension is well-defined because all bases of a given vector space have the same cardinality. This is a nontrivial theorem, not an obvious fact. A priori, you might worry that one basis could have 3 vectors and another could have 4. But this cannot happen: any two bases of the same space are in bijection. (In the finite-dimensional case, this is proved by the Steinitz exchange lemma; the infinite-dimensional case requires the axiom of choice.) Because the basis size is invariant, dimension is an intrinsic property of the space — it does not depend on which basis you happen to choose.\n",
